    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Hypostyle halls, such as a palace or audience hall, typically of stone construction with columns, in Persia or other places. Examples are reception halls in the palaces of Achaemenid rulers at Susa and Persepolis distinguished by six rows of six columns and three columned porticos, each with two rows of six columns. These structures may have functioned as audience halls for the king's court and visiting foreign vassals and ambassadors.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000050633/Frankfort, Art and Architecture of the Ancient Orient (1970)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000050631/Shaw and Jameson, Dictionary of Archaeology (1999)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Ontvangsthallen in de paleizen van Achaemenidische heersers in Susa en Persepolis met zes rijen van zes zuilen en drie zuilengangen met elk twee rijen van zes zuilen. Deze constructies hebben mogelijk gediend als audiëntiezalen voor het hof van de koning en de ontvangst van bezoekende vazallen en ambassadeurs uit andere landen.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>古波斯阿卡曼尼(Achaemenid)王朝之皇宮迎賓大廳，位於蘇薩(Susa)及其首都普希波里斯(Persepolis)。其特色為具有六列柱子，每列六根，以及三個柱廊。這些建築的功能如同宮廷的覲見大廳，以及接見國外封臣及大使的地方。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079740/AS-Academia Sinica data (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Empfangshalle in den Palästen von achämenidischen Herrschern in Susa und Persepolis. Sie zeichnen sich durch sechs Reihen mit je sechs Säulen und drei mit Säulen versehenen Portiken, jeder mit zwei Reihen von sechs Säulen. Dieser Bau hat möglicherweise als Audienzsaal für den königlichen Hof und für den Empfang ausländischer Vasallen und Botschafter gedient.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
